
AST body emission parses executable bodies against the completed environment.
This is where source statements and expressions become typed AST.

The goal is strict, local semantics.
Expression evaluation finds the natural type.
Contextual coercion is applied only by the frontend site that owns the receiving boundary.

## Main paths

- `src/compiler_frontend/ast/module_ast/emission/`
- `src/compiler_frontend/ast/expressions/`
- `src/compiler_frontend/ast/statements/`
- `src/compiler_frontend/ast/field_access/`
- `src/compiler_frontend/type_coercion/`
- `src/compiler_frontend/value_mode.rs`

## Body emission

`emit_ast_nodes` parses function, start and template bodies against the completed environment.
It validates function terminality, emits AST nodes and emits const-template output.

It owns:

- executable body parsing
- body-local declarations
- expression parsing
- expression type checking
- receiver lookup
- field access
- builtin member validation
- call validation
- operator result typing
- contextual coercion at owned boundaries
- function terminality validation

Body-local declarations use shared declaration-shell syntax where appropriate, but they are not participants in top-level dependency sorting.

## Expression typing

Expression evaluation determines the natural type of an expression.
It stays strict.

Contextual coercion is applied only at explicit receiving sites such as:

- declarations
- assignments
- returns
- template/string content
- explicit `cast` target boundaries
- backend/prelude call contracts
- struct fields
- choice payload fields
- collection and map entries
- default values
- `then` arms whose enclosing value-producing block has an explicit receiver

Generic parameter slots are not cast targets.
Generic inference doesn't look through `cast`.

## Access modes

`value_mode.rs` tracks frontend access classification for bindings, expressions, call arguments and receiver use.

Mutability and reference state stay separate from semantic type identity.
Runtime ownership is a later borrow/lowering concern.

A `~T` parameter accepts either explicit `~place` for an existing mutable place or a fresh rvalue that HIR can materialise into a hidden local before borrow validation.
`~` remains place-only source syntax.

## Runtime expressions before HIR

Runtime expressions that can't fold are currently represented in AST as stack-oriented RPN node vectors before HIR lowering.

Those expression vectors are expression-only structures, not broad statement fragments.
`ExpressionKind::Runtime` carries `ExpressionRpn`.
Copy expressions carry `PlaceExpression`.
`ExpressionKind::ValueBlock` is the only expression variant allowed to carry statement bodies.

This keeps expression handling explicit while HIR still owns final control-flow lowering.

## Value-producing blocks

Value-producing blocks are not general expressions.
They produce one or more values at closed receiving sites.

Supported producers include:

- value-producing `if`
- full match
- block-form `catch:` recovery

Valid receiving sites include declarations, assignments, multi-bind, returns and nested `then`.
They are rejected in function arguments, operator operands, constructor arguments, collection literals, template interpolation and expression statements.

AST must enforce the receiver arity on every producing path.

## Terminality

AST validates terminality before HIR lowering.

Non-unit success returns must be statically terminal.
`assert(false)` and `assert(false, "message")` are statically terminal.
Dynamic `assert(condition)` isn't.

If HIR later sees a non-unit function that can fall through, HIR reports an internal transformation invariant.
The user-facing source diagnostic should have happened in AST.

## Diagnostics

AST expression and statement diagnostics are user-facing.
Use `CompilerDiagnostic` with source locations and structured reason payloads.

Good diagnostics should explain the boundary that failed:

- expected type versus actual type
- invalid receiving context
- invalid access mode
- missing mutable access marker
- unavailable receiver method
- invalid terminal path
- unsupported deferred syntax

Type diagnostics should carry semantic `TypeId`s and render through `DiagnosticRenderContext`.
Don't clone `DataType` values into diagnostic payloads once semantic types exist.

## Common mistakes

- Applying contextual coercion from the callee side instead of the receiving boundary.
- Treating `~` as a type shape rather than access syntax.
- Letting value-producing blocks behave like general expressions.
- Letting HIR diagnose a user terminality error AST should catch.
- Passing untyped or syntax-level `DataType` through expression checking after resolution.
- Re-resolving imports from raw tokens during body emission.

